\contentsline {figure}{\numberline {1.1}{\ignorespaces Affine unit of an artificial neuron. The input vector $\bm {x}$ is scaled by the weight vector $\bm {w}$, shifted by the bias $b$, and converted into the pre-activation response $z$ before a non-linear activation is applied.}}{4}{figure.caption.8}%
\contentsline {figure}{\numberline {1.2}{\ignorespaces Comparison of common activation functions. Rectified Linear Unit (ReLU), Leaky ReLU, Exponential Linear Unit (ELU), and Gaussian Error Linear Unit (GELU) preserve a mostly linear positive branch, while sigmoid and hyperbolic tangent (tanh) saturate at both extremes.}}{6}{figure.caption.9}%
\contentsline {figure}{\numberline {1.3}{\ignorespaces Fully connected Multi-Layer Perceptron (MLP) showing layer-wise information flow from input features to hidden representations and output predictions. The arrows represent weighted connections, and the highlighted path shows one possible route from an input feature to an output neuron.}}{7}{figure.caption.11}%
\contentsline {figure}{\numberline {1.4}{\ignorespaces Complete Encoder-Decoder Transformer architecture. The encoder memory matrix $\bm {H}_{\text {enc}}$ (highlighted in blue) is fed to all decoder layers for cross-attention. Residual connections (curved arrows) enable stable gradient flow throughout the network.}}{15}{figure.caption.20}%
\contentsline {figure}{\numberline {1.5}{\ignorespaces Transformer encoder layer architecture. The input embedding (Emb.) is combined with positional information, processed by self-attention and a Feed-Forward Network (FFN), and stabilized by residual connections with Layer Normalization (LayerNorm).}}{15}{figure.caption.22}%
\contentsline {figure}{\numberline {1.6}{\ignorespaces Transformer decoder layer architecture. The decoder contains masked self-attention for previous target tokens, cross-attention for reading encoder outputs, and a Feed-Forward Network (FFN), each wrapped with residual connections and Layer Normalization (LayerNorm).}}{16}{figure.caption.24}%
\addvspace {10\p@ }
\contentsline {figure}{\numberline {2.1}{\ignorespaces Comparison of unstructured, semi-structured, and structured sparsity patterns in a weight matrix. White cells indicate removed weights. Unstructured sparsity scatters zeros freely across the matrix; semi-structured sparsity enforces a fixed retention ratio within each local group; structured sparsity removes entire rows or columns, yielding a dense submatrix.}}{28}{figure.caption.36}%
\contentsline {figure}{\numberline {2.2}{\ignorespaces Sparsity schedules for iterative pruning targeting 90\% sparsity over $R$ rounds. Cubic and cosine schedules slow down near the target, giving the model time to stabilise before the final mask is frozen; linear and step schedules do not.}}{33}{figure.caption.40}%
\contentsline {figure}{\numberline {2.3}{\ignorespaces Post-training pruning pipeline. A small calibration set is forwarded through the frozen model to collect layer-wise activation statistics. These are used to score each weight or group, after which the lowest-scoring units are zeroed out. An optional weight correction step adjusts the remaining weights to compensate for the removed ones. No gradient update to the pretraining loss is performed at any stage.}}{34}{figure.caption.41}%
\addvspace {10\p@ }
\contentsline {figure}{\numberline {3.1}{\ignorespaces Taxonomy of the pruning methods considered in this chapter. The classification crosses the pruning unit, sparsity topology, optimization signal, recovery stage, deployment objective, and evaluation regime.}}{41}{figure.caption.43}%
\contentsline {figure}{\numberline {3.2}{\ignorespaces Second-order compensation strategies for unstructured and semi-structured pruning. SparseGPT removes one scalar weight per step and compensates using one column of $\hat {H}^{-1}$, while MRP removes an N:M group jointly and uses the block $(\hat {H}^{-1}_{MM})^{-1}$ to model interactions among simultaneously removed weights.}}{47}{figure.caption.53}%
\contentsline {figure}{\numberline {3.3}{\ignorespaces ZipLM pipeline. The global phase benchmarks attention-head and FFN configurations and searches for layer-wise sparsity profiles satisfying the required speedup. The local phase applies second-order structured pruning through inverse-Hessian scoring, compensation updates, and iterative Hessian refinement.}}{49}{figure.caption.56}%
\contentsline {figure}{\numberline {3.4}{\ignorespaces EvoPress $(1+\lambda )$ evolutionary search loop for dynamic LLM compression \citep {evopress2024}. The method applies budget-preserving level-switch mutation and progressively evaluates candidates with larger calibration budgets.}}{50}{figure.caption.59}%
\contentsline {figure}{\numberline {3.5}{\ignorespaces DarwinLM search loop \citep {darwinlm2025}. The method first builds a sparsity-level database with OBS-style structured pruning, then performs training-aware evolutionary selection over stitched candidate models.}}{52}{figure.caption.61}%
